        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="Tb9EWfqgxNUa7GMe5I4A-29" parent="1" style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;whiteSpace=wrap;rounded=0;" value="Example&lt;br&gt;SPA could be drawing app and web service could be cloud file storage&amp;nbsp;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="96" width="174" x="976" y="1018" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="Tb9EWfqgxNUa7GMe5I4A-30" parent="1" style="rounded=0;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fillColor=#dae8fc;strokeColor=#6c8ebf;" value="&lt;div&gt;code_verify is high entropy&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;t = transformation method (S256)&lt;/div&gt;code_challenge = t(code_verifier)&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: transparent; color: light-dark(rgb(0, 0, 0), rgb(255, 255, 255));&quot;&gt;plain transformation method should be avoided and requires encryption&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="99" width="244.5" x="-39.5" y="858" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="Tb9EWfqgxNUa7GMe5I4A-31" parent="1" style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;whiteSpace=wrap;rounded=0;" value="A malicious program on device&lt;div&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: transparent; color: light-dark(rgb(0, 0, 0), rgb(255, 255, 255));&quot;&gt;might already have the client ID and secret&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: transparent; color: light-dark(rgb(0, 0, 0), rgb(255, 255, 255));&quot;&gt;might be able to read the authz code in the response&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: transparent; color: light-dark(rgb(0, 0, 0), rgb(255, 255, 255));&quot;&gt;might be able to read the code_challenge in the request&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The authz code can only be used once. It may be revealed to an attacker after it is received and before it is used by the legitimate requesting client.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;What if a malicious program reads the code_verifier?&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The code_verifier can only be used once.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;An attacker cannot use it if the legitimate requester already used it. Since the legitimate requester does not reveal the code_verifier until requesting the authz code, it leaves little time for the attacker to use the code_verifier if stolen.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;What if a malicious program reads the access token or refresh token?&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div id=&quot;copyshrugemoji__shrug_emoji_text&quot;&gt;¯\_(ツ)_/¯ Original spec assumed that they can be kept secure&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The security of these values varies by platform and device. PKCE is useful mitigation, not a guarantee. It is up to the stakeholders of the device and its software to keep these values secure.&lt;/div&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="386.5" width="384" x="-420" y="872.5" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="Tb9EWfqgxNUa7GMe5I4A-32" parent="1" style="rounded=0;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fillColor=#dae8fc;strokeColor=#6c8ebf;" value="client id, client secret, redirect URI, and state not shown here&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;redirect URIs use a custom scheme/protocol and don&#39;t point to a web server&lt;/div&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="88" width="198.24" x="-7" y="725" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="Tb9EWfqgxNUa7GMe5I4A-34" parent="1" style="rounded=0;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fillColor=#dae8fc;strokeColor=#6c8ebf;" value="Instead of giving the AS a redirect URI in step 3, it could already know the redirect URI associated with the given client ID. It is best to register a client&#39;s redirect URI before authz requests and it is required for public clients." vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="90" width="236" x="-286" y="475.32000000000005" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
